Lab 15: Dealing with measurement errors in our data

Author

Jesse Brunner

Published

April 23, 2025

In all of our models so far we have been assuming that the predictor variables are measured perfectly. That is, while we acknowledge that we measure the responses with some error (e.g., we use a normal distribution to describe the sampling variation around some expectation or mean), we have not been doing the same with our predictor variables. Letâs change that.

Before doing so, however, it is worth thinking about whether doing so should be our default. After all, we rarely measure our predictors without some error! Even in experiments there can be error. For instance, we might apply a given amount of fertilizer, but maybe we measure it imperfectly or maybe the amount of nutrients that gets to the plant varies. Should we acknowledge this in our models?

Like all things in statistical analyses, there are rarely simple, universal recommendations1. One the one hand, if you have measured something fairly precisely, the small errors remaining are not likely to introduce a lot of extra uncertainty. If, however, there is a fair amount of measurement uncertainty then ignoring it would give you a false sense of precision. These errors might even introduce bias. If measurement errors are symmetric around the mean and not associated with particular values of predictors or the outcomes, then you might be safe2, but often these errors cause you to estimate a flatter slope. If instead you measure small (or large) values with less precision, you have less precision in certain kinds of groups or treatments or outcomes (e.g., maybe you cannot measure the size of animals that died as well as those that survived, or vice versa), then those measurement errors are very likely to bias your estimates of key relationships.

Instead of guessing how safe you are or are not, itâs best to draw your DAG, simulate some data, and convince yourself (and your reviewers) that youâre dealing with the issue correctly.

Simple measurement error

Tree seed rain

For one of our final examples, letâs imagine we were interested in plant reproductive output (i.e., seed production, S) as a function of nitrogen in the soil (N). This might be an observational study or an experiment in which the soil was fertilized; it really doesnât matter for how we model it. But I guess so that weâre all on the same page letâs say it is an observational study and we are measuring the mass of seeds (rather than counts) in seed baskets around twenty trees. We also estimate the amount of free nitrogen in the soil by taking three soil samples, running some sort of test, and then averaging the quantities so we have a single value of N for each tree.

library(dagitty)
library(rethinking)
Warning: package 'cmdstanr' was built under R version 4.4.3
Ndag <- dagitty("dag{
N -> S
}")
coordinates(Ndag) <- list(
  x=c(N=3,  S=6),
  y=c(N=5,  S=5))
drawdag(Ndag)

Itâs a pretty simple DAG, yes? But actually, we donât know the True amount of nitrogen in the soil, we just have observed values, so our DAG should look something like this

Ndag2 <- dagitty("dag{
e_N -> N_obs <- N -> S
e_N [unobserved]
N [unobserved]
}")
coordinates(Ndag2) <- list(
  x=c(e_N=1, N_obs=1, N=3,  S=5),
  y=c(e_N=1, N_obs=5, N=5,  S=5))
drawdag(Ndag2)

Here you can see that while N is what is causing seed production (S), we can only observe Nobs, which is a function of (or caused by) the True but unobserved value of N as well as some error process.

Simulating data with observation error

Letâs simulate the data given this causal structure. It should echo what I just said, but it is also pretty much exactly how weâll model the data.

set.seed(42)

n <- 40 # number of trees
Ntrue <-  rnorm(n=n, mean=5, sd=1.5) # True N (I have no idea what these should be!)

# parameters of linear model
a <- 3
b <- 1

Seeds <- rnorm(n=n, 
              mean = a + b*(Ntrue-5), 
              sd = 1)

plot(Seeds ~ Ntrue)

So far this is just what weâve done in the past. But the point (in this example) is that we do not observe Ntrue, but rather Nobs.

sd_N <- 1

Tree <- rep(1:n, each=3)

# three measurements of N for each tree
Nobs3 <- rnorm(n=length(Tree), 
               mean=Ntrue[Tree], 
               sd=sd_N)

# average the measurements of N for each tree to there's a single measurement
Nobs <- numeric(n)
for(i in 1:n){
  Nobs[i] = mean(Nobs3[Tree == i])
}

The important thing here is that Ntrue is the expected value for Nobs, we simply add on some measurement error. Just like in our DAG, above, Ntrue causes both seed mass as well as the observed values of Nobs.

What does this look like compared to the Truth?

plot(Seeds ~ Ntrue, xlim=range(Ntrue, Nobs))
points(x=Nobs, y=Seeds, col = "red", pch=20)
arrows(x0=Ntrue, x1=Nobs, y0=Seeds, length=1/10, col="red")

So we can see that some observed values of N are far from the True value. Letâs see what this means for our goal of estimating the relationship between N and seed production.

Fitting a model given omniscience

Letâs first fit a model using the True values of soil nitrogen as if we had perfect data. This is just good point of comparison. Again, in reality we couldnât do this.

dat <- list(Seeds=Seeds, 
            Ntrue=Ntrue, 
            Nobs=Nobs)

m_true <- ulam(
  alist(
    Seeds ~ normal(mu, sd),
    mu <- a + b*(Ntrue-5), 
    a ~ normal(4, 2),
    b ~ normal(0, 1),
    sd ~ exponential(1)
  ), 
  data=dat
)
precis(m_true)
        mean         sd      5.5%    94.5%      rhat ess_bulk
a  3.0785884 0.13812900 2.8291118 3.291859 0.9991465 474.2119
b  0.9918748 0.08491628 0.8548479 1.125792 1.0192584 422.5869
sd 0.9412288 0.10162271 0.7937491 1.123884 1.0001048 475.5607

And for completeness, and so we have the code for the next iterations, letâs plot this relationship.

genPreds <- function(df, model, n=1e4, lo=0.055, hi=0.945){
  preds <- rethinking::link(fit=model, data=df, n=n)
  df$preds_mean <- apply(X=preds, MARGIN=2, FUN = mean)
  df$preds_lo <- apply(X=preds, MARGIN=2, FUN = quantile, prob=lo)
  df$preds_hi <- apply(X=preds, MARGIN=2, FUN = quantile, prob=hi)
  return(df) 
}


preds_true <- data.frame(
  Ntrue = seq(from=min(Ntrue, Nobs), 
               to=max(Ntrue, Nobs), 
               length.out=50)
)

preds_true <- genPreds(df=preds_true, model = m_true)

plot(Seeds ~ Ntrue, type = "n")
lines(x=preds_true$Ntrue, y=preds_true$preds_mean)
lines(x=preds_true$Ntrue, y=preds_true$preds_lo, lty=2)
lines(x=preds_true$Ntrue, y=preds_true$preds_hi, lty=2)

Fitting a naive model with Nobs, but pretending it is perfect

Now letâs use the predictor we would have, Nobs, but without acknowledging that it might be wrong. It is identical to the prior model, only substituting Nobs for Ntrue.

m_obs <- ulam(
  alist(
    Seeds ~ normal(mu, sd),
    mu <- a + b*(Nobs-5), 
    a ~ normal(4, 2),
    b ~ normal(0, 1),
    sd ~ exponential(1)
  ), 
  data=dat
)
precis(m_obs)
        mean        sd      5.5%    94.5%      rhat ess_bulk
a  3.1203319 0.1949048 2.7985773 3.425763 0.9983412 348.6403
b  0.8909596 0.1030975 0.7249396 1.049051 1.0000457 415.7782
sd 1.1525637 0.1445791 0.9544695 1.402997 0.9988659 529.5330

The output is a bit different than the model using True values of the predictor, but itâs not terrible. More than anything we just get less precision in our estimates (and the slope tends to be a bit flatter in repeated simulations).

preds_obs <- data.frame(
  Nobs = seq(from=min(Ntrue, Nobs), 
               to=max(Ntrue, Nobs), 
               length.out=50)
)

preds_obs <- genPreds(df=preds_obs, model = m_obs)

plot(Seeds ~ Ntrue, type = "n")
# True model
lines(x=preds_true$Ntrue, y=preds_true$preds_mean)
lines(x=preds_true$Ntrue, y=preds_true$preds_lo, lty=2)
lines(x=preds_true$Ntrue, y=preds_true$preds_hi, lty=2)
# Model with observed values
lines(x=preds_obs$Nobs, y=preds_obs$preds_mean, col="red")
lines(x=preds_obs$Nobs, y=preds_obs$preds_lo, lty=2, col="red")
lines(x=preds_obs$Nobs, y=preds_obs$preds_hi, lty=2, col="red")

And we can compare their estimates of the slope, which was our goal in this analysis.

dens( extract.samples(m_true)$b, adj=1) 
dens( extract.samples(m_obs)$b, adj=1, col = "red", add=T)

Why are the predictions of these two models so close? Largely because we have a fair bit of data and while we have errorsâobserved values of N that are shifted to the left or right of their true valuesâthose errors tend to cancel out in this case. We wonât always be so lucky, so letâs see how to model this with the structure we used to create the data.

Fitting a less naive model

We now model the predicted seed mass as a function of the estimated âTrueâ value of nitrogen (called N_True to distinguish it from Ntrue, which we would not actually know). But we also have to model the relationship between what we observed, Nobs, and the âTrueâ values. This is formulated as Nobs ~ normal(N_True, Nsd), which might be the reverse of what you expected.

Remember, we are saying that our observations come from a distribution with an expectations or mean values of N_True. (N_True is a vector, with one value for each observation.) It does not matter that we donât know N_True and instead need to estimate it; the relationship is what is important. Or put another way, if our model knows that a value of Nobs came from a distribution with some unobserved mean, N_True, it can infer what those values of N_True must be to produce the observed value, Nobs. (We also get it to estimate the standard deviation of the error distribution.)

The only tricky bits (beyond these slightly unintuitive concepts) are getting ulam to code things right. We need to tell it that N_True is a vector of length N, which I now specify in the data and then we need to use a trick in codingâN_True[i] instead of N_True in the linear modelâto ensure the data types match up on the left and right-hand side of the equation for mu.

dat$N <- length(dat$Nobs)

m_full <- ulam(
  alist(
    Seeds ~ normal(mu, sd),
    mu <- a + b*(N_True[i]-5), # <- notice the subsetting... necessary to get the data types to match.
    
    Nobs ~ normal(N_True, Nsd), 
    vector[N]:N_True ~ normal(5, 2),
    
    a ~ normal(4, 2),
    b ~ normal(0, 1),
    sd ~ exponential(2),
    Nsd ~ exponential(2)
  ), 
  data=dat
)
precis(m_full)
40 vector or matrix parameters hidden. Use depth=2 to show them.
         mean        sd       5.5%    94.5%     rhat  ess_bulk
a   3.1118079 0.1746526 2.83115755 3.406292 1.081280 28.122436
b   1.0374771 0.1566563 0.78799013 1.284697 1.481290  2.012861
sd  0.6828245 0.4630729 0.05169757 1.246859 1.645392  1.745396
Nsd 0.6507803 0.3975633 0.10674075 1.182495 1.661852  1.645920

Well all of that for not much, huh? This model fit like crap, our effective sample sizes are super low, and you likely got some divergent transitions or an E-BFMI less than 0.3. What gives?

Letâs see whatâs going on, and a plot can help a lot.

# NB: pairs is not letting me extract the correct parameters, so we'll do this manually
samp_full <- extract.samples(m_full)

str( samp_full[2:5] )
List of 4
 $ a  : num [1:500, 1] 3.04 3.05 3.05 3.1 3.08 ...
 $ b  : num [1:500, 1] 1.07 1.06 1.07 1.07 1.07 ...
 $ sd : num [1:500, 1] 0.0467 0.0319 0.0398 0.0332 0.0249 ...
 $ Nsd: num [1:500, 1] 1.11 1.09 1.09 1.11 1.16 ...
samp_full <- samp_full[2:5]

lattice::splom(as.data.frame(samp_full))

Notice that the standard deviation representing the measurement error for seed masses, sd, is strongly, negatively correlated to the standard deviation of the measurement error for nitrogen concentrations, Nsd. Allowing for more variation in either one of these measurements implies more precision in the other; there is no way to disentangle them.

I would like to point out that even though this model sucked, it did estimate the slope more accurately (if less precisely) than the model that just naively assumed no error in measurements in N.

b_true <- extract.samples(m_true)$b
b_obs <- extract.samples(m_obs)$b
b_full <- extract.samples(m_full)$b

dens(b_true, xlim=c(0,2), adj=1)
dens(b_obs, add=T, col="red", adj=1)
dens(b_full, add=T, col="blue", adj=1)

Also, it is worth seeing that even though this model does suck quite a lot, it is doing a reasonably good job of estimating the True values of nitrogen. It is certainly closer, on average, than the observed values of nitrogen.

plot(x=Ntrue, 
     y=colMeans( extract.samples(m_full)$N_True ), 
     col="blue", ylab = "Measured (red) or inferred (blue) value of N"
)
points(x=Ntrue, y=Nobs, col="red")
abline(a=0, b=1)

So it is âworkingâ in a way. It is just a really inefficient model because it has two parameters trying to do the same thing.

Solutions to the less naive model

What are our options? What should we do about this poor-sampling model?

First, we might just be OK using the naive model, assuming we demonstrate to ourselves with simulations that our estimates are not (too) biased.

Second, we might have some way of constraining the priors for, say, Nsd so that we donât have two free parameters. For instance, perhaps we have some outside data on the variability in estimates of soil nitrogen that we can use to construct a more informative prior for this parameter.

Third, if we have estimates of the standard deviation in our estimate of soil nitrogen for each treeâwe took three soil samples and averaged them, after all, so we could also calculate a standard deviationâwe could include that as data in our model rather than something to be estimated! (This is what McElreath did in his marriage/divorce example in the book.)

Fourth, if we actually had multiple observations of soil nitrogen for each tree we could model these observations directly and have the model estimate the standard deviation across all soil samples for all trees rather than assuming that our estimates of the standard deviations are made without error.

Recall that we simulated the three soil nitrogen measurements for each tree. We will use these to try options 3 & 4.

Option 3

dat$N_sd <- numeric()
for(i in 1:dat$N){
  dat$N_sd[i] <- sd( Nobs3[Tree==i] )
}

So now we have an estimate of the standard deviation of nitrogen measurements for each tree that we can feed into the model as data.

Our model is just as above, with the exception that N_sd is now data rather than an estimated parameter

m_opt3 <- ulam(
  alist(
    Seeds ~ normal(mu, sd),
    mu <- a + b*(N_True[i]-5), # <- notice the subsetting... necessary to get the data types to match.
    
    Nobs ~ normal(N_True, N_sd), 
    vector[N]:N_True ~ normal(5, 2),
    
    a ~ normal(4, 2),
    b ~ normal(0, 1),
    sd ~ exponential(2)
  ), 
  data=dat
)
precis(m_opt3)
40 vector or matrix parameters hidden. Use depth=2 to show them.
        mean         sd      5.5%    94.5%      rhat ess_bulk
a  3.1583001 0.16411797 2.8973654 3.417605 0.9982142 511.2455
b  1.0028069 0.09502125 0.8421459 1.149645 0.9991465 219.9685
sd 0.7976066 0.17235467 0.5525405 1.085152 1.0029600 163.3060

This model that treats the standard deviation of errors in nitrogen measurements as data runs much, much more efficiently, yes?

And it does so without causing biases in estimates, like we observed (a bit) in the naive model.

b_opt3 <- extract.samples(m_opt3)$b

dens(b_true, xlim=c(0,2), adj=1)
dens(b_obs, add=T, col="red", adj=1)
dens(b_full, add=T, col="blue", adj=1)
dens(b_opt3, add=T, col="green", adj=1)

In some cases it does a better job of predicting the True values of soil nitrogen, too, sometimes works, although often it does not matter much (on average).

plot(x=Ntrue, 
     y=colMeans( extract.samples(m_full)$N_True ), 
     col="blue", 
     ylab = "Measured (red) or inferred (blue, green) value of N"
)
points(x=Ntrue, y=Nobs, col="red")
points(x=Ntrue, 
       y=colMeans( extract.samples(m_opt3)$N_True ), 
       col="green")
abline(a=0, b=1)

The way we have simulated our data, where there is essentially constant error in measurements, is the best-case scenario. You can imagine that if error increased (or decreased) with the value of nitrogen, we would tend to have a stronger bias in our estimates. Accounting for the different reliabilities in measurements, as this model does, can save such an analysis.

Option 4

Now, finally, letâs fit the model to the observed values of nitrogen, directly.

Note that I changed Nobs, which was an average for each tree, to N_obs, which is a vector with three observations per tree.

dat$Tree <- Tree
dat$N_obs <- Nobs3
str(dat)
List of 7
 $ Seeds: num [1:40] 5.26 1.79 4.3 3.22 2.24 ...
 $ Ntrue: num [1:40] 7.06 4.15 5.54 5.95 5.61 ...

Also note that I changed N_sd, which was data in the last model, back to Nsd, which represents the standard deviation among nitrogen measurements.

m_opt4 <- ulam(
  alist(
    Seeds ~ normal(mu, sd),
    mu <- a + b*(N_True[i]-5), # <- notice the subsetting... necessary to get the data types to match.
    
    N_obs ~ normal(N_True[Tree], Nsd[Tree]), 
    vector[N]:N_True ~ normal(5, 2),
    
    vector[N]:Nsd ~ exponential(2),
    
    a ~ normal(4, 2),
    b ~ normal(0, 1),
    sd ~ exponential(2)
    
  ), data=dat
)
precis(m_opt4)

So either of these last two models seems to work pretty well.
